BYD announced 2Q25 results on 29 August: revenue was up \(14\%\) YoY/18% QoQ at RMB201bn. Gross profit margin came in at \(16.3\%\) down 0.9ppt YoY/down 3.8ppt QoQ, and we attribute the QoQ margin decline to higher depreciation cost, more rebate (RMB1bn) to its dealers, and price competition. However, sales contribution from both export sales \((22.5\%)\) and high- end brand sales \((7.7\%)\) rose YoY in 2Q25 vs. 1Q25 (see Exhibit 2). BYD's operating (clean EBIT) margin was \(1.4\%\) down 3.9ppt YoY/down 1.9ppt QoQ, mainly on higher R&D expense. 2Q25 net income came in at RMB6.4bn, down \(31\%\) YoY, missing consensus by around \(30\%\) .

Based on BYD Electronic (BYDE)'s \((65.76\%\) owned by BYD) 2Q25 earnings of RMB1.1bn, we estimate BYD's net profit per vehicle could be around RMB4.9k in 2Q25, down \(43\%\) YoY/down \(44\%\) QoQ (see Exhibit 1). Although we expect 3Q25 volume sales will decline QoQ based on its orders intake, we expect BYD's NP per car will gradually recover into 3- 4Q25, supported by cost cut and OPEX saving initiatives, slower capacity expansion, more contribution from exports and premium brands sales, aimed by the launch of Titanium 7, Yangwang U7L, and Denza N8L, with higher GPM contribution.

We factor in 2Q25 results and cut our 2025/26/27E revenue by \(4\% /5\% /7\%\) . Net- net, we trim 2025/26/27E earnings by \(21\% /16\% /11\%\) , respectively. Our PO for BYD- H/BYD- A is HKD141/USD18 (HKD158/USD20 earlier)/RMB128 (RMB144 earlier) to reflect updated earnings (see details inside). We maintain Buy on BYD as we expect BYD will improve its car spec and performance via enhanced autonomous driving system, \(2^{\text{nd}}\) Gen blade battery, and new chassis and suspension technology to more of its EV models in 2026, to help demand. Besides, we expect BYD to have stricter cost/OPEX saving plans in next few quarters. See page 5 for valuation details.

Our PO is HKD141 per share (USD18 per ADR). We derive our PO using a sum- of- the- parts (SOTP) valuation.

EV business - we apply \(1.4xP / S\) to BYD's average 2025- 26E EV sales. Our target multiple of \(1.4xP / S\) is slightly higher than peers, which we think is fair as given industry leadership in the EV segment and better autonomous driving technology.

External EV and ESS battery sales - we apply \(1.4xP / S\) to its average 2025- 26E external EV and ESS battery sales. Our target multiple of \(1.4xP / S\) is slightly higher than peers, which we believe to be justified given 1) industry leadership in the EV battery segment, 2) improved LFP blade battery and enhanced charging speed.
BYDE: we apply \(20xP / E\) to BYDE's average 2025- 26E EPS in our SOTP, in line with peers average.

Downside risks: failure to improve operational metrics, as measured by plant utilization, average engine size, new energy vehicle (NEV) competition, supply chain and operation challenges amid tariff resurgence in China.
Our PO for BYD- A is RMB128. We derive our PO by applying RMB/HKD exchange rate and \(0\%\) premium (last one years' average) to SOTP valuation for BYD- H given it is a dual- listed stock.

EV business - we apply \(1.4xP / S\) to BYD's average 2025- 26E EV sales. Our target multiple of \(1.4xP / S\) is slightly higher than peers, which we think is fair as given industry leadership in the EV segment.

External EV and ESS battery sales - we apply \(1.4xP / S\) to its average 2025- 26E external EV and ESS battery sales - \(1.4xP / S\) is similar to peers' average, fair in our view due to similar business nature and earnings growth outlook.
BYDE: we apply \(20xP / E\) to BYDE's average 2025- 26E EPS in our SOTP, in line with peers average.

Downside risks: failure to improve operational metrics, as measured by plant utilization, average engine size, new energy vehicle (NEV) competition, supply chain and operation challenges amid Tariff resurgence in China.
